Review: Blocking

Written byiMisut 30/06/202329/06/2023
17 Comments

Introduction

A strategic game in three dimensions. Run smart moves and set strategic blocks to try to get the tallest towers that multiply your points.

This is how we are presented with Blocking, a design by Timo Diegel (Conus Wabantus, Mimanca). First published in 2019 by Clemens Gerhards.

It is not published in Spanish, so you will have to resort to import (the game is completely independent of the language). It allows games to 2 players, with a suggested minimum age of 10 years and a duration of between 20 and 30 minutes. The sale price to the public is 55 euros. A copy of the color edition of Clemens Gerhards has been used for this review (there is another edition with the board in natural wood color).

Important: If you already know the game and/or you are only interested in my opinion on it, you can move directly to the Opinion section. The Content and Mechanics sections are especially intended for those who don't know the game and prefer to get a general idea of how it works.



Content

Inside a cardboard box of two pieces (cover and bottom), of dimensions of 26.5 to6,5-4,5 cm. (medium square box similar to Big Shot), we find the following elements:

  • Table (wood)
  • 3 Pawns (wood)
  • 9 Block (wood) markers
  • 44 Control markers (22 of each color) (wood)
  • Bag (of fabric)
  • Regulation

Mechanics

Blocking is an abstract for two in which the goal is to try to create towers in orthogonal interconnected squares with pieces of player color at the top. To do this, in each turn, you must move one of the three neutral pawns (red, green and blue) a minimum of two steps in any direction (orthagonal or diagonal) and then place a piece of the player's color in any adjacent box (orthagonal or diagonal) available, placing on top of it 2 blocking pieces (of the 3 that there are) of the color of the displaced pawn. A box will be available if free or occupied by a stack of control parts of a height of less than four and without locking tab. The game ends when none of the pawns can be displaced, after which the players score as many points as the number of boxes occupied by each group multiplied by the number of pieces in the largest stack contained in the group. However, loose pieces (one box alone and with height 1) will subtract points.


Basic concepts

Let's start with the board. We find a square of seven squares per side that have been erased the four corners of the corners, so that the board in total will have only 45 boxes.

3 Pawns of three different colors (red, green and blue) will move on these boxes. These pawns will be neutral and can be displaced by any player through orthogonal rectilinear or diagonal movements crossing only empty boxes, not being able to cross by occupied boxes, either by another pawn or by control markers. The second restriction is that these movements must be at least 2 squares away.

When you activate a pawn, players will place Control markers in an adjacent, orthogonal or available box. One box available is one that is free or either that has a control marker tower of less than four, placing the marker on top of that stack. A box with a height tower 4 will no longer be a box available. At the end of the game the players will score points by groups of boxes connected to each other orthogonally controlled by their markers (a tower is controlled by the player to whom the scoreboard belongs at the top of that tower) depending on the height reached by the highest tower within that group. However, loose chips (high towers 1) will apply a penalty.

One of the peculiarities of the game is that it incorporates a timed system that temporarily blocks the boxes right after placing a control marker on them. To do this, 3 Block Markers (which give name to the game) are available for each pawn color, so that, when placing a control marker adjacent to the displaced pawn, two of the corresponding color block markers were also placed on that marker, preventing no player from placing a control marker on top at least in the next two turns.

We have enough of this.


Preparation of the Departure

  1. The board is placed in the center of the table.
  2. A general reservation with the block markers is formed.
  3. One of the neutral pawns is placed in the central box of the board.
  4. Each player picks a color and receives 22 control markers.
  5. The starting player is randomly chosen. This one takes one of the two neutral pawns available and places it in any free box on the board. His rival also comes with the remaining pawn.

We can start now.


Development of the Departure

A blocking game develops over an undetermined number of turns alternated by the players, starting with the starting player.

On each turn, the active player shall decide on three steps in the following order:

  1. Move a Neutral Pawn. The player must choose any of the three neutral pawns and move it in a straight line (orthogonal or diagonal) at least 2 boxes, not being able to cross boxes occupied by control markers or other neutral pawns.
  2. Place a Control Scoreboard on an Available Box. A box available shall be any of the boxes adjacent to the displaced pawn (orthagonal or diagonal) that is free (without pawns or markers) or that is occupied by a marker or a marker tower of less than 4 height without block markers on it.
  3. Place Block Markers. The player will place 2 color locking markers collected from 2 different boxes corresponding to the pawn displaced on the newly placed control marker. At the beginning of the game the 3 block markers will be available. After the first displacement of a certain pawn, 2 block markers of its color will be placed on the marker. After the second movement of that pawn, the marker will be placed that is still available plus a marker of the 2 that were placed previously. From this moment on there would always be one box with 2 markers and another with 1 marker of the color of that pawn and, when it is moved, a marker must be removed from each of those two boxes (leaving the one that had 2 with only 1, and the one that had 1 will be free of blocking markers).

After this, the turn passes to the opposite player.


End of the Departure

The game can be completed in two ways:

  • Let a player place all his control markers.
  • That none of the three neutral pawns can legally move.

After this, the final count would be conducted, in which each player scores:

  • For each group of orthogonally connected boxes controlled by a player, the player scores as many points as the number of boxes occupied by the height of the highest tower contained in that group. An isolated box with a tower 2 or more is also considered a group.
  • The player is penalized for the isolated boxes he controls with loose chips (high one) in triangular progression, that is, he will lose 1/3/6/10/15/... points by controlling 1/2/3/4/5/... isolated boxes.

The player with the most points will be the winner.


Personal Opinion

Today we will talk about a virtually unknown game if we stick to the statistics published in the BGG. Today only thirty-four users have it marked on property and only has twelve ratings. I think they are data that make it clear that it is a game that virtually no one has on the radar, even within the niche of abstracts, really, (you know, perfect information, absence of random elements and relatively intense confrontation on a common playing field).

And it's funny, because, although it wasn't the game with which I discovered that paradise for lovers of abstracts such as the publisher Clemens Gerhards (that was an accident since I bought an abstract for one without looking very well at the characteristics of the game), it was one of the first of its designs I tried. And I didn't want to let more time without talking about him.

Blocking is one of those abstracts that might not seem like anything from the other world. Even powerfully remember other existing games. As a summary, the goal of the players is to try to form groups of boxes orthogonal adjacent to each other with their control markers. In turn, the value of the group will depend on the maximum height present in one of the boxes of the group, since the players can dispute the control of these boxes by stacking markers over others previously placed, although not being able to exceed a maximum height of four.

However, the interesting mechanical detail is that in order to place these markers the players will have to move one of three neutral pawns, each with a different color. This pawn can move any number of boxes in a straight line (orthagonal or diagonal) in any direction as long as its movement covers a minimum of two squares without crossing boxes occupied by other elements. After making this move, the active player will place one of his markers in any adjacent box of those surrounding the displaced pawn (orthagonals or diagonals), provided that in that box you can place a marker when you are free, or have a stack of markers that does not reach height four.

Now the key detail. On the placed marker shall be placed 2 locking discs of the color of the displaced pawn, so that the box will be blocked as long as there are at least one of these discs on the top marker of the stack. In order to remove these markers it will be necessary to move the pawn of the corresponding color twice, since the two discs that are placed on the new marker will come from the two boxes in which there are markers (in one there will be two and there will be one, and in another there will be one and will run out of block markers). Of course, the box on which there are two block markers, after the next displacement of the pawn of the corresponding color, will become a single disc, preventing even placing control markers on it.

The game will end when the players exhaust their reserve of color markers or, failing that, that a legal movement cannot be resolved because the three neutral pawns are blocked (they cannot move at least two squares in one direction), proceeding to a final count in which the players, in addition to being rewarded by the groups of controlled boxes interconnected with each other according to the highest height in any of these boxes, will be penalized for controlling isolated boxes with loose pieces (if it is a tower two or higher no longer penalizes). And it will do so in triangular progression.

All this leads to a tense start from minute one, in which each player will try, on the one hand, to generate the groups of controlled boxes connected to each other larger possible, while, on the other hand, he will try to prevent the rival from getting the same. This is where the genius of using neutral pawns comes into play and, above all, the use of the block markers that prevent you from undoing a play early.

In the beginning, because the player who wants to prevent in future shifts that a position he has won can be controlled by the rival will try to keep the neutral pawns away from trajectories that allow them to be stopped in boxes that give them access to those positions. But they will also try not to displace the neutral pawn to which the block markers belong, forcing the rival to be the one who moves them to try to lift the veto to occupy that box.

Of course, this having three pawns that each can move in eight directions with the only restriction of the minimum distance makes each turn allow a range of options that make it quite difficult to calculate, making Blocking a rather tactical game. But as the board closes and the options decrease, movements gain more and more weight, raising the tension.

The issue of heights is also very relevant, as it is equal or more important to raise at least one group tower in height, as it is equivalent to raising the value of each of those boxes of the group (as if everyone had that height). Of course, the ideal is to get height four, but this is something our rival will try to avoid at all costs and, on the way, using that tower snatched for its own benefit.

Then it's also very interesting to play with the isolated pieces. Every time we see the opportunity to isolate rival boxes because the more accumulate, the greater the points sang, something that can prove crucial in the final count.

If you have a certain baggage in the world, it is possible that what I have told you will remind you very much of the designs of Dirk Hen, author of Alhambra. I mean Rosenk?nig (here her tochorreseña). A game in which the premise is very similar, that is, a neutral pawn that players displace on a griddled board on which control markers are left trying to form groups of controlled boxes interconnected orthogonally to each other. But there are three very important differences that make this Block a better design, at least as pure abstract.

The first is that the room for manoeuvre depends entirely on the players' decision and not on a deck of cards that adds alepathality. It is true that in both pawns can end up blocked early, but in Blocking it is a decision made to the lemon among the players, sometimes accidentally, sometimes intentionally.

The second is that the limitation of the capture of boxes is transferred to the number of markers that can be placed in it, and not to a limited number of catches for the whole game, which generated an interesting dynamic, but which took over the development of the game, becoming a war of attrition. Here the fight for the boxes is more fierce.

And the third is that the score in Henn's game was exponential, while in Block is linear, so the game will remain much more equal until the end. In Rosenk?nig there could be games in which a date was impossible due to the combination of chance and the position of the scoreboard on the board.

I have few cons to put on this design. Perhaps the already commented on that uncertain finale can happen abruptly if the players are somewhat sloppy in the early games and, unintentionally, end up blocking all the scoreboards early. But it is a minutiae compared to the elegance it distills and as with very simple rules, a dynamic is achieved so entertaining and tense thanks, precisely, to this possibility of eliminating options by placing markers in the escape routes of the pawns so that they can no longer move in the remainder of the game.

Let's move on to the production. As always with Clemens Gerhards, we find a high-density, thick wooden board (we can use it as a throwing weapon). Pawns and markers show generic shapes. The box is still corrugated cardboard with a sticker on the front and in the singing that, although it has its charm, is still somewhat poor. The regulation is well structured and leaves no doubt.

And we're closing. Blockage is an abstract for two with very simple ideas. Ideas that, although not especially original, the way in which genius is used in this design is not popular. It's an easy game to explain but it admits a significant amount of moves, especially at the start of the game. The theme of the blocks is the soul of the game, both when disabling boxes with the markers of the corresponding colors or reaching the maximum height, as well as when it comes to annulling the pawns themselves. It's tense, it's fun and, above all, it gives rise to very different games thanks to that uncertainty of not knowing when the last movement is going to happen. Of the best games, if not the best, of those available in the catalogue of this publisher. For all this I give you a...
